I love Chinese cuisine - both American and traditional styles. So, having tried countless restaurants, I'm pleased to say this is my favorite.  Shanghai Tokyo (ST) is located on highway 1 near the University of Maryland, College Park. There are other restaurants, a walking trail, and metro-rail station nearby as well. Across the street on the same side of the highway is a convenient pay-to-park lot - it's pretty cheap in comparison to other parking lots in the DC Metro area.  ST isn't huge, and offers a naturally lit, relaxed ambiance. The staff are quite friendly, and have offered some flavorful recommendations. I often go with friends so that we can eat family-style and I can get to taste as many of the dishes as possible. Last time, we had the Ma Po Tofu, Beef with Peppers, beef Chow Mein, Chicken Mei Fun, and Four Season Green Beans.  Each were exquisite. The tofu was cooked well and lightly spicy as done in Sichuan. The green beans had a mix of spice, umami, salt, and pepper to give a well balanced profile. Both of the noodle dishes had tender meat and noodles NOT too saucy. Lastly, the beef with long peppers was spicy, yet well-seasoned.  In addition to Chinese food, the restaurant also has Thai and Japanese cuisines as well. I've had both their curries and sushis before and they were also great.  Overall, this place has some of the best Asian food I've ever had. I can't recommend ST enough.

The last two times I ordered drinks, they never included the drink with the order, and when I brought it up they didn’t even apologize for forgetting and acted as if I caused them a huge inconvenience by asking for what I ordered.  However, it was my most recent experience here that convinced me to never come here again.  I ordered Honey Sesame Chicken from here recently and was horrified to find STAPLES in my food (takeout)! One was at the top of the food in plain sight - so I have no idea how whoever packaged this food missed this. There was another staple submerged in the sauce. This is absolutely unacceptable! At that point, I threw away the order.  I have no idea how to submit a complaint against them for this (I tried doing my own research and the PG County Health Dept. They routinely make me feel as though my presence in the restaurant is bothering them and keeping them from whatever else they would rather be doing at the time.  I have stood in line and watched staff members ask a customer for their order, then immediately cut the customer off, pick up the phone, and take the phone order instead. During my most recent visit alone, this happened to two customers, including myself, which is why I've decided to make this post.  I thought this would be the end of the review, but as I was being handed my carry-out order, I noticed a half-eaten apple with bites taken from it sitting directly on the food prep counter. This is an unacceptable health code violation, which I intend to report.  Needless to say, I will not be visiting or recommending this place until improvements are made.
